<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06180094 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06180094 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  USSR; STATE; YUGOSLAVIA; US; EUROPE; MEETING; COUNTRY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The United States and its principal allies expect soon to convene anemergency, pan-European meeting that would consider solutions for the crisisin Yugoslavia, but senior U.S. officials said Thursday that no one has anyworkable ideas about how to halt the slide toward dissolution and civil war inthe Balkan country.;    The officials, who asked not to be identified, said ameeting would probably be held in Vienna next week under new emergencyprovisions of the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe (CSCE),composed of 33 European countries plus the United States and Canada.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  U.S., ALLIES PLAN EMERGENCY TALKS ON BALKANCRISIS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Mercury News wire services contributed to this report.See also related story on page 1A in this section  </MEMO><TEXT>     The officials said the participants will probably be represented by theirCSCE ambassadors but said the session could lead to a foreign ministers'meeting if the Yugoslav situation continues to deteriorate.;    &quot;There is nota hell of a lot that we or our European friends can do beyond trying to workthrough mechanisms like the CSCE,&quot; one official said. &quot;No one contemplates anykind of multilateral military intervention. But even when it comes topolitical and diplomatic action, we're all still working our way through theprocess.&quot;;    'National aspirations';  Secretary of State James Baker appealedto Yugoslavia's central government Thursday to find a peaceful way in whichsecessionist republics could express their &quot;national aspirations.&quot;;    &quot;We arevery distressed about what we see happening,&quot; Baker told reporters in againregistering U.S. concern that the declared secessions of Slovenia and Croatiacould lead to Yugoslavia's disintegration.;    In an effort to ease thesituation, Baker and White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater on Wednesdaysuggested the republics be granted greater autonomy and sovereignty within aunited Yugoslavia.;    Baker went a step further Thursday.;    &quot;We really hopethe Yugoslav people, the republics and the central government can find a wayto give vent to the national aspirations of the various elements in Yugoslaviain a peaceful way through negotiations and dialogue,&quot; Baker said.;    U.S.offers no solution;  He offered no formula, however, for bringing this aboutexcept to stress that any arrangement must be a peaceful one that alsopreserves Yugoslavia as a nation.;    At a meeting in Berlin last week, CSCEforeign ministers appealed to Croatia and Slovenia to remain within thenational federation and urged Serbia, the most powerful republic, to negotiatewith the others on changes in the governmental structure that would preserveYugoslavia's political and territorial integrity.;    Senior U.S. officialselaborated Thursday on the administration's call for negotiation. They saidthe United States and its European allies believe that a peaceful outcome canbe achieved by agreement to restructure Yugoslavia into a confederation thatwould give greatly increased powers to the constituent republics whileretaining a symbolic but minimal central government.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Washington Post  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910628  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  20A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  464  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday June 28, 199100180094,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>